The consensus definition of Artificial Intelligence (AI) can be summarized in the following five bullet points based on insights from various research papers:

1. **Lack of a Universal Definition**: There is no universally accepted definition of AI, leading to a variety of interpretations and approaches in its study and application [(Waser, 2009)](https://consensus.app/papers/what-artificial-general-intelligence-clarifying-goal-waser/d878a94bfe725a61b010e249e7f8c4a0/?utm_source=chatgpt).

2. **Interdisciplinary Nature**: AI is an interdisciplinary field, involving contributions from computer science, psychology, linguistics, philosophy, and neurobiology, among others. This diversity of disciplines contributes to the complexity of defining AI [(Pfeifer, 1988)](https://consensus.app/papers/intelligence-models-emotion-pfeifer/76202609456a5fc5a9577d7457534315/?utm_source=chatgpt).

3. **Emphasis on Autonomy and Decision-making**: AI often includes the study of semi-autonomous and autonomous systems that assist or replace human decision-making processes [(Gicquello, 2020)](https://consensus.app/papers/intelligence-international-arbitration-gicquello/502b0a9019c1596b9471dfc747c3bf76/?utm_source=chatgpt).

4. **Focus on Intelligence as a Feature**: AI research often centers around the concept of intelligence as a notable feature of both human beings and machines, though there is no consensus on the scientific understanding of intelligence in either domain [(Gregg, 2018)](https://consensus.app/papers/coming-challenges-artificial-intelligence-gregg/fc652ce5874857eab522e3e365f6d108/?utm_source=chatgpt).

5. **Involvement of Machine Learning and Knowledge Representation**: AI research includes significant work on knowledge representation and machine learning, though there is no consensus on the best methods for representing knowledge [(Pfeifer, 1988)](https://consensus.app/papers/intelligence-models-emotion-pfeifer/76202609456a5fc5a9577d7457534315/?utm_source=chatgpt).

